item.title: Differentiation
item.author: user@example.com (Hugo Author)
item.description: Normally if without any statements, \( f \) is a real-valued continuous function on \( [a,b] \) Definition of differentiation Definition For a function \(f\), defined on interval \([a,b]\). For \(x \in [a,b ]\) \[\lim_{t \to x } \frac{f(t) - f(x)}{t - x} \] is called the differentiate of f at x, denotes by \(f’(x)\). Apparently, to let \(f’(x)\) exists, the function has to have left/right limit (or both) at the point \(x\).

item.description: Doom modules Modules Doom has this lovely modular configuration base that takes a lot of work out of configuring Emacs. item.title: Physics 2 adv. lecture note
item.author: user@example.com (Hugo Author)
item.description: Electromagnetism Electric Force Net force: \( \vec{F_{R}} = \vec{F}_{1 \text{ on } q} + \vec{F}_{2 \text{ on } q} + \dots\) Electric force is similar to the gravitational but varies inversely, like \( \lim x \text{ and } \lim \frac{1}{x} \) Unlike there is only attaction in gravitation, electrical has repulsion. Electric charge Coulomb’s law \[ F = k_e \frac{q_1q_2}{r ^2} \vec{\mathbf{r}}\] Note:\( k_e = \frac{1}{4 \pi \epsilon_{0}} \sim 8.99* 10 ^{9} \) and \( \vec{r} \) is the unit vector on the direction.
